    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-08-26T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-08-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="889"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d889">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/13015.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Vice Consul <persName type="from">Silliman</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mexico</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-26">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 26, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Zapata’s attitude toward Carranza is decidedly unfriendly. He states that a
                    conference between Carranza and himself is imperative, and must be at his own
                    military camp forty miles due south of Cuernavaca; he will not meet Carranza
                    elsewhere. He is holding some 2,000 Constitutionalists whom he has disarmed.</p>
                <p>The Brazilian Minister and myself called upon the First Chief to-day. He said he
                    would not go to the military camp and continues to belittle Zapata.</p>
                <p>Villa emissaries are with Zapata and are treated with the highest
                    consideration.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Silliman</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
